# Resonance II: sites $jq_n$, $j\in\mathbb{Z}\backslash \{0\}$

In this section, we deal with resonances arising from sites $jq_n$, $j\in\mathbb{Z}\backslash\{0\}$.

<div id="thm2" class="theorem">

**Theorem 9**. *Assume $j\in\mathbb{Z}$ satisfies $0<  |j |\leq 2\frac{b_{n+1}}{q_n}+10$. Then we have $$\label{g1000}
            r_{j}  \leq   \exp\{- \frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta_{j} -C\varepsilon)q_n\}(r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}})+ \exp\{- (L-2\beta_{j} -C\varepsilon)q_n\}(r_{j+1}+r_{j-1}).$$*

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* Take $\phi(j q_n+rq_n)$ with $|r|\leq 10\varepsilon$ into consideration. Denote by $p=jq_n+rq_n$. Without loss of generality assume $j>0$. Let $n_0$ be the least positive integer such that $$q_{n-n_0}\leq  \frac{ \varepsilon}{2}  (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon) q_n.$$ Let $s$ be the largest positive integer such that $sq_{n-n_0}\leq (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon) q_n$. By the fact that $(s+1)q_{n-n_0}\geq (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon)q_n$, one has $$s\geq \frac{1}{\varepsilon}$$ and $$\label{2sq}
            (\frac{1}{4}-3\varepsilon)q_n \leq sq_{n-n_0}\leq (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon)q_n.$$

Set $I_1, I_2\subset \mathbb{Z}$ as follows $$\begin{aligned}
            %
            I_1 &=& [- 2s q_{n-n_0},-1], \\
            I_2 &=& [ j q_n  -2sq_{n-n_0},j q_n+ 2sq_{n-n_0}-1 ],

\end{aligned}$$ and let $\theta_m=\theta+m\alpha$ for $m\in I_1\cup I_2$. The set $\{\theta_m\}_{m\in I_1\cup I_2}$ consists of $6sq_{n-n_0}$ elements. Let $k=6s q_{n-n_0}-1$.

By modifying the proof of   and   (or Appendices in   and  ), we can prove the claim (Claim 2): for any $m\in I_1\cup I_2$, one has ${\rm Lag}a_m\leq  2q_n (\beta_{j}+ \varepsilon)$. We also give the proof in the Appendix.

Applying Lemma <a href="#Le.Uniform" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.Uniform">3</a>, there exists some $j_0$ with $j_0\in I_1\cup I_2$ such that $$\label{g121}
            |P_k(\theta_{j_0}-\frac{k-1}{2}\alpha)| \geq e^{kL-2(\beta_{j} +\varepsilon)q_n}.$$

Let $$\label{2g4}
            I=[j_0-3sq_{n-n_0} +1,j_0+3sq_{n-n_0}-1]=[x_1,x_2].$$

By <a href="#g100" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g100">[g100]</a>, <a href="#g121" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g121">[g121]</a> and <a href="#2sq" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2sq">[2sq]</a>, one has

- I: $j_0\in I_1$. Then for any $y_1$ with $|y_1|\leq 10 \varepsilon q_n$, $$\begin{aligned}
                  |\phi(y_1)| \leq &e^{-kL+2\beta_{j} q_n+\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,y_1-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
                  |P_{[y_1+1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|)\nonumber\\
                  \leq &e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+ C\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,y_1-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
                  |P_{[y_1+1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|).\label{12g2}

  \end{aligned}$$

- II: $j_0\in I_2$. Then for any $y_2$ with $|y_2-jq_n|\leq 10 \varepsilon q_n$, $$\label{2g2}
                  |\phi(y_2)| \leq e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,y_2-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
                  |P_{[y_2+1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|).$$

Clearly, $$I_1\subset [-\frac{q_n}{2},0]$$ and $$I_2\subset [jq_n-\frac{q_n}{2} ,jq_n+\frac{q_n}{2}].$$ **Case 1:** $j_0\in [jq_n-\frac{1}{4} q_n, jq_n]\cap I_2$

Let $x=j_0-(jq_n-\frac{1}{4}q_n)$. Therefore, $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{4}q_n$ and $$x_1=jq_n-q_n+x \in[jq_n-q_n,jq_n-\frac{3}{4}q_n]$$ and $$x_2=jq_n+\frac{1}{2}q_n+x \in [jq_n+\frac{1}{2}q_n,jq_n+\frac{3}{4}q_n].$$

<div class="center">

</div>

In Fig.3, $x_1$ and $x_2$ locate at the red part. $j_0$ locates at the blue part. The numbers above are the sites after deducting $jq_n$.

By Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a>, one has that $$\label{2g7}
            |\phi(x_1^\prime)\leq r_{j-1} e^{-L  x+C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)+C\varepsilon q_n}$$ and $$\label{2g8}
            |\phi(x_2^\prime)\leq r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L x +C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j+1}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2}-x) +C\varepsilon q_n} .$$ By <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a>, one has $$\label{2g1}
            |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|\leq e^{ L(q_n-x)+C\varepsilon q_n},$$ and $$\label{2g0}
            |P_{[p+1,x_2]}|\leq e^{ L(\frac{q_n}{2}+x)+C\varepsilon q_n}.$$

By <a href="#2g2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g2">[2g2]</a>-<a href="#2g0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g0">[2g0]</a>, one has that $$\begin{aligned}
            |\phi(p)|\leq& e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n }    |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|(r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L x } +r_{j+1}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2}-x)} )\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n } |P_{[p+1,x_2]}|(r_{j-1} e^{-L  x} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)}  ) \nonumber\\
            \leq& e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n }(    |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L x } + e^{L(q_n-x)}r_{j+1}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2}-x)} )\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n }e^{ L(\frac{q_n}{2}+x)}(r_{j-1} e^{-L  x} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)}  ) \nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j+1}+r_{j-1})+e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n +2L x+C\varepsilon q_n} r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n-L x+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            \leq& e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j+1}+r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}})\label{g501}\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n-L x+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}},\label{g41}

\end{aligned}$$ where the last inequality holds by the fact that $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{4}q_n$.

The term in <a href="#g501" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g501">[g501]</a> decays, so we are going to bound <a href="#g41" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g41">[g41]</a>.

<div class="center">

</div>

Clearly, $x_1+q_n\in[jq_n, jq_n+\frac{1}{4}q_n]$. By Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a>, one has that $$\label{2g30}
            |\phi(x_1'+q_n)\leq r_{j} e^{-L  x+C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)+C\varepsilon q_n} .$$ By <a href="#g100" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g100">[g100]</a>, <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a> and <a href="#2g30" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g30">[2g30]</a>, one has for any $y$ with $|y-jq_n-\frac{1}{2} q_n|\leq 10 \varepsilon q_n$, $$\begin{aligned}
            |\phi(y)|\leq&  |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1}  e^{L \frac{q_n}{2}+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j} e^{-L  x} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)})\\
            &+|P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1} e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x+C\varepsilon q_n)} r_{j+1}.

\end{aligned}$$ This implies $$\begin{aligned}
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\leq&  |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1}  e^{L \frac{q_n}{2}+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j} e^{-L  x} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)})\\
            &+|P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1} e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x+C\varepsilon q_n)} r_{j+1}.

\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, we have $$\begin{aligned}
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}&  |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{ C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j} e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}- x)} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{Lx}+  e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x)} r_{j+1}). \label{g37}

\end{aligned}$$

By Lemma <a href="#klem1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="klem1">7</a>, one has $$\label{g38}
            | P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}- P_{[{x}_1,p-1]}|\leq e^{(L+C\varepsilon) q_n-Lx-\beta q_n}.$$ By <a href="#g37" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g37">[g37]</a> and <a href="#g38" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g38">[g38]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            |P_{[{x}_1,p-1]}|   &r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} \nonumber\\
            \leq & e^{ L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x)+ C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j}  +   r_{j+1})  + e^{C\varepsilon q_n}( e^{Lx}+e^{(L-\beta) q_n-Lx} )r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\label{g39}

\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, $$\begin{aligned}
            |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}  & e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n-L x+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}\nonumber\\
            \leq & e^{C\varepsilon q_n}(e^{- (L-2\beta_{j}  ) \frac{1}{2}q_n-2L x} +e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}) r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} \nonumber\\
            &+e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n-2L x+C\varepsilon q_n}(r_j+r_{j+1})\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{C\varepsilon q_n} (r_j e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n}+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) \frac{q_n}{2}}+ r_{j+1} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n})\label{g40}

\end{aligned}$$

By <a href="#g40" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g40">[g40]</a>, <a href="#g501" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g501">[g501]</a> and <a href="#g41" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g41">[g41]</a>, one has $$\label{g42}
            |\phi(p)| \leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}+r_j+r_{j+1})+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$ Therefore, $$\label{g43}
            r_{j}\leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}+r_j+r_{j+1})+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$ By the fact that $L >2\beta \geq 2\beta_{j}-\varepsilon$, we have $$e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j\leq\frac{1}{2}r_j$$ and hence $$\label{g44}
            r_{j}\leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) q_n} (r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}+r_{j+1})+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$

**Case 2**: $j_0\in [jq_n, jq_n+\frac{1}{4} q_n]\cap I_2$

In this case, by the similar proof of <a href="#g44" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g44">[g44]</a>, we have

$$\label{g45}
            r_{j}\leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) q_n} (r_{j+1}+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}+r_{j-1})+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$

$$\begin{aligned}
            %
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} &\leq&  e^{-\frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta_{j}- C\varepsilon)q_n} r_{j}+e^{-\frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta_{j}- C\varepsilon)q_n}r_{j+1} \nonumber\\
            & &+ e^{C\varepsilon q_n}(e^{-(L-2\beta_{j})\frac{q_n}{2}  }+e^{  -L\frac{q_n}{4}}) r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}. \label{g24}

\end{aligned}$$

Since $\varepsilon$ is small and $L>2\beta \geq 2\beta_{j}-\varepsilon$, one has that $$e^{C\varepsilon q_n}(e^{-(L-2\beta_{j})\frac{q_n}{2}  }+e^{  -L\frac{q_n}{4}})  r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\leq \frac{1}{2}   r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}.$$

Therefore, (<a href="#g24" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="g24">[g24]</a>) becomes $$\label{g25}
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\leq  \exp\{-\frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta_{j}- C\varepsilon)q_n\}(r_j+r_{j+1}).$$

**Case 3:** $j_0\in [jq_n + \frac{5}{8}q_n,jq_n+\frac{3}{4}q_n]\cap I_2$

Let $x=j_0-jq_n -\frac{5}{8}q_n$. Therefore, $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{8}q_n$, $x_1=jq_n +\frac{q_n}{4}+x$ and $x_2=jq_n+ q_n+x$.

By Lemmas <a href="#klem2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="klem2">5</a> and <a href="#klem1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="klem1">7</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            |   P_{[p+1,x_2]} | 
            &\leq   |   P_{{[p+1-jq_n-q_n,x_2-jq_n-q_n]}} | +e^{C\varepsilon q_n} e^{L(\frac{1}{2}q_n+x)  -\beta_{j} q_n} \nonumber\\
            &\leq e^{C\varepsilon q_n} e^{L(\frac{1}{2}q_n-x)}+e^{C\varepsilon q_n} e^{L(\frac{1}{2}q_n+x)  -\beta_{j} q_n} \label{g171}

\end{aligned}$$ Replacing <a href="#g17" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g17">[g17]</a> with <a href="#g171" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g171">[g171]</a> and following the proof of Case 2, we also have that $$\label{g26}
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\leq  \exp\{-\frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta_{j}- C\varepsilon)q_n\}(r_j+r_{j+1}).$$

If $j_0\in I_1$, one has that $$x_1\in[-\frac{5}{8}q_n,-\frac{3}{8}q_n],x_2\in [\frac{1}{8}q_n, \frac{3}{8}q_n].$$ By <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a>, one has $$\label{gg100}
            |P_{[x_1,-1]}| \leq e^{ L|x_1|+C\varepsilon q_n},   |P_{[1,x_2]} | \leq e^{ L|x_2|+C\varepsilon q_n}.$$ By <a href="#g100" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g100">[g100]</a>, <a href="#g1091" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g1091">[g1091]</a>, <a href="#sq" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="sq">[sq]</a>, <a href="#g68" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g68">[g68]</a> and <a href="#gg100" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg100">[gg100]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            |\phi(0)| \leq& e^{-kL +\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
            |P_{[1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|)\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{-\frac{3}{4}Lq_n+C\varepsilon  q_n } (e^{L|x_1|} +e^{L|x_2|})\nonumber\\
            \leq &\frac{1}{2} \nonumber.

\end{aligned}$$ This is impossible since $\phi(0)=1$. Therefore, we must have $j_0\in I_2$ and Theorem <a href="#thm1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm1">8</a> follows from <a href="#g23" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g23">[g23]</a>, <a href="#g25" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g25">[g25]</a> and <a href="#g26" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g26">[g26]</a>. ◻

</div>

# Resonance II: sites $jq_n$, $j\in\mathbb{Z}\backslash \{0\}$

In this section, we deal with resonances arising from sites $jq_n$, $j\in\mathbb{Z}\backslash\{0\}$.

<div id="thm2" class="theorem">

**Theorem 9**. *Assume $j\in\mathbb{Z}$ satisfies $0<  |j |\leq 2\frac{b_{n+1}}{q_n}+10$. Then we have $$\label{g1000}
            r_{j}  \leq   \exp\{- \frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta_{j} -C\varepsilon)q_n\}(r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}})+ \exp\{- (L-2\beta_{j} -C\varepsilon)q_n\}(r_{j+1}+r_{j-1}).$$*

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* Take $\phi(j q_n+rq_n)$ with $|r|\leq 10\varepsilon$ into consideration. Denote by $p=jq_n+rq_n$. Without loss of generality assume $j>0$. Let $n_0$ be the least positive integer such that $$q_{n-n_0}\leq  \frac{ \varepsilon}{2}  (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon) q_n.$$ Let $s$ be the largest positive integer such that $sq_{n-n_0}\leq (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon) q_n$. By the fact that $(s+1)q_{n-n_0}\geq (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon)q_n$, one has $$s\geq \frac{1}{\varepsilon}$$ and $$\label{2sq}
            (\frac{1}{4}-3\varepsilon)q_n \leq sq_{n-n_0}\leq (\frac{1}{4}-2\varepsilon)q_n.$$

Set $I_1, I_2\subset \mathbb{Z}$ as follows $$\begin{aligned}
            %
            I_1 &=& [- 2s q_{n-n_0},-1], \\
            I_2 &=& [ j q_n  -2sq_{n-n_0},j q_n+ 2sq_{n-n_0}-1 ],

\end{aligned}$$ and let $\theta_m=\theta+m\alpha$ for $m\in I_1\cup I_2$. The set $\{\theta_m\}_{m\in I_1\cup I_2}$ consists of $6sq_{n-n_0}$ elements. Let $k=6s q_{n-n_0}-1$.

By modifying the proof of   and   (or Appendices in   and  ), we can prove the claim (Claim 2): for any $m\in I_1\cup I_2$, one has ${\rm Lag}a_m\leq  2q_n (\beta_{j}+ \varepsilon)$. We also give the proof in the Appendix.

Applying Lemma <a href="#Le.Uniform" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.Uniform">3</a>, there exists some $j_0$ with $j_0\in I_1\cup I_2$ such that $$\label{g121}
            |P_k(\theta_{j_0}-\frac{k-1}{2}\alpha)| \geq e^{kL-2(\beta_{j} +\varepsilon)q_n}.$$

Let $$\label{2g4}
            I=[j_0-3sq_{n-n_0} +1,j_0+3sq_{n-n_0}-1]=[x_1,x_2].$$

By <a href="#g100" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g100">[g100]</a>, <a href="#g121" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g121">[g121]</a> and <a href="#2sq" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2sq">[2sq]</a>, one has

- I: $j_0\in I_1$. Then for any $y_1$ with $|y_1|\leq 10 \varepsilon q_n$, $$\begin{aligned}
                  |\phi(y_1)| \leq &e^{-kL+2\beta_{j} q_n+\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,y_1-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
                  |P_{[y_1+1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|)\nonumber\\
                  \leq &e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+ C\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,y_1-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
                  |P_{[y_1+1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|).\label{12g2}

  \end{aligned}$$

- II: $j_0\in I_2$. Then for any $y_2$ with $|y_2-jq_n|\leq 10 \varepsilon q_n$, $$\label{2g2}
                  |\phi(y_2)| \leq e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n } (|P_{[x_1,y_2-1]}| |\phi (x_2^\prime)|+
                  |P_{[y_2+1,x_2]} | |\phi (x_1^\prime)|).$$

Clearly, $$I_1\subset [-\frac{q_n}{2},0]$$ and $$I_2\subset [jq_n-\frac{q_n}{2} ,jq_n+\frac{q_n}{2}].$$ **Case 1:** $j_0\in [jq_n-\frac{1}{4} q_n, jq_n]\cap I_2$

Let $x=j_0-(jq_n-\frac{1}{4}q_n)$. Therefore, $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{4}q_n$ and $$x_1=jq_n-q_n+x \in[jq_n-q_n,jq_n-\frac{3}{4}q_n]$$ and $$x_2=jq_n+\frac{1}{2}q_n+x \in [jq_n+\frac{1}{2}q_n,jq_n+\frac{3}{4}q_n].$$

<div class="center">

</div>

In Fig.3, $x_1$ and $x_2$ locate at the red part. $j_0$ locates at the blue part. The numbers above are the sites after deducting $jq_n$.

By Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a>, one has that $$\label{2g7}
            |\phi(x_1^\prime)\leq r_{j-1} e^{-L  x+C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)+C\varepsilon q_n}$$ and $$\label{2g8}
            |\phi(x_2^\prime)\leq r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L x +C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j+1}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2}-x) +C\varepsilon q_n} .$$ By <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a>, one has $$\label{2g1}
            |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|\leq e^{ L(q_n-x)+C\varepsilon q_n},$$ and $$\label{2g0}
            |P_{[p+1,x_2]}|\leq e^{ L(\frac{q_n}{2}+x)+C\varepsilon q_n}.$$

By <a href="#2g2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g2">[2g2]</a>-<a href="#2g0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g0">[2g0]</a>, one has that $$\begin{aligned}
            |\phi(p)|\leq& e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n }    |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|(r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L x } +r_{j+1}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2}-x)} )\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n } |P_{[p+1,x_2]}|(r_{j-1} e^{-L  x} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)}  ) \nonumber\\
            \leq& e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n }(    |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L x } + e^{L(q_n-x)}r_{j+1}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2}-x)} )\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}Lq_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n }e^{ L(\frac{q_n}{2}+x)}(r_{j-1} e^{-L  x} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)}  ) \nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j+1}+r_{j-1})+e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n +2L x+C\varepsilon q_n} r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n-L x+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            \leq& e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j+1}+r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}})\label{g501}\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n-L x+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}},\label{g41}

\end{aligned}$$ where the last inequality holds by the fact that $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{4}q_n$.

The term in <a href="#g501" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g501">[g501]</a> decays, so we are going to bound <a href="#g41" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g41">[g41]</a>.

<div class="center">

</div>

Clearly, $x_1+q_n\in[jq_n, jq_n+\frac{1}{4}q_n]$. By Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a>, one has that $$\label{2g30}
            |\phi(x_1'+q_n)\leq r_{j} e^{-L  x+C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)+C\varepsilon q_n} .$$ By <a href="#g100" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g100">[g100]</a>, <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a> and <a href="#2g30" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g30">[2g30]</a>, one has for any $y$ with $|y-jq_n-\frac{1}{2} q_n|\leq 10 \varepsilon q_n$, $$\begin{aligned}
            |\phi(y)|\leq&  |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1}  e^{L \frac{q_n}{2}+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j} e^{-L  x} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)})\\
            &+|P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1} e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x+C\varepsilon q_n)} r_{j+1}.

\end{aligned}$$ This implies $$\begin{aligned}
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\leq&  |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1}  e^{L \frac{q_n}{2}+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j} e^{-L  x} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{2} -x)})\\
            &+|P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|^{-1} e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x+C\varepsilon q_n)} r_{j+1}.

\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, we have $$\begin{aligned}
            r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}&  |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{ C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j} e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}- x)} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{Lx}+  e^{L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x)} r_{j+1}). \label{g37}

\end{aligned}$$

By Lemma <a href="#klem1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="klem1">7</a>, one has $$\label{g38}
            | P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}- P_{[{x}_1,p-1]}|\leq e^{(L+C\varepsilon) q_n-Lx-\beta q_n}.$$ By <a href="#g37" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g37">[g37]</a> and <a href="#g38" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g38">[g38]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            |P_{[{x}_1,p-1]}|   &r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} \nonumber\\
            \leq & e^{ L(\frac{q_n}{2}-x)+ C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j}  +   r_{j+1})  + e^{C\varepsilon q_n}( e^{Lx}+e^{(L-\beta) q_n-Lx} )r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\label{g39}

\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, $$\begin{aligned}
            |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}  & e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n-L x+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}\nonumber\\
            \leq & e^{C\varepsilon q_n}(e^{- (L-2\beta_{j}  ) \frac{1}{2}q_n-2L x} +e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}) r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} \nonumber\\
            &+e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n-2L x+C\varepsilon q_n}(r_j+r_{j+1})\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{C\varepsilon q_n} (r_j e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n}+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) \frac{q_n}{2}}+ r_{j+1} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n})\label{g40}

\end{aligned}$$

By <a href="#g40" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g40">[g40]</a>, <a href="#g501" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g501">[g501]</a> and <a href="#g41" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g41">[g41]</a>, one has $$\label{g42}
            |\phi(p)| \leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}+r_j+r_{j+1})+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$ Therefore, $$\label{g43}
            r_{j}\leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} (r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}+r_j+r_{j+1})+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$ By the fact that $L >2\beta \geq 2\beta_{j}-\varepsilon$, we have $$e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j\leq\frac{1}{2}r_j$$ and hence $$\label{g44}
            r_{j}\leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) q_n} (r_{j-1}+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}+r_{j+1})+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$

**Case 2**: $j_0\in [jq_n, jq_n+\frac{1}{4} q_n]\cap I_2$

In this case, by the similar proof of <a href="#g44" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g44">[g44]</a>, we have

$$\label{g45}
            r_{j}\leq  e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) q_n} (r_{j+1}+r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}+r_{j-1})+r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-(L-2\beta _{j} -C\varepsilon) \frac{q_n}{2}}.$$

**Case 3**: $j_0\in[jq_n-\frac{1}{2}q_n, jq_n-\frac{1}{4}q_n]\cap I_2$

In this case, let $x=j_0-(jq_n-\frac{1}{2}q_n)$. It is easy to see that $0\leq x\leq \frac{q_n}{4}$, $$x_1=jq_n-\frac{5q_n}{4}+x \in[jq_n-\frac{5}{4}q_n, jq_n-q_n]$$ and $$x_2=jq_n+\frac{1}{4}q_n+x\in [jq_n+\frac{q_n}{4}, jq_n+\frac{q_n}{2}].$$

<div class="center">

</div>

By Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a>, one has that $$\label{2g44}
            |\phi(x_1^\prime)\leq r_{j-1} e^{-L  (\frac{q_n}{4}-x)+C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j-\frac{3}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4} +x)+C\varepsilon q_n}$$ and $$\label{2g45}
            |\phi(x_2^\prime)\leq r_{j} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4} +x) +C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) +C\varepsilon q_n} .$$

By <a href="#2g2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g2">[2g2]</a>, <a href="#2g44" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g44">[2g44]</a> and <a href="#2g45" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g45">[2g45]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            r_j&\leq e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[p+1,x_2]}| (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j-1}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j-\frac{3}{2}})\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|  (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}).\label{g63}

\end{aligned}$$

\end{aligned}$$

We are going to bound $$\label{gg102}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[p+1,x_2]}| (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j-1}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j-\frac{3}{2}})$$ and $$\label{gg101}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|  (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j+\frac{1}{2}})$$ separately.

By <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a>, one has $$\label{g47}
            |P_{[p+1,x_2]}|\leq e^{L(\frac{1}{4}q_n+x) +C\varepsilon q_n}.$$ By <a href="#g47" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g47">[g47]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n} &|P_{[p+1,x_2]}|  (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j-1}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j-\frac{3}{2}})\nonumber\\
            %
            %
            \leq    &  e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+2Lx+C\varepsilon q_n}   r_{j-1}+ e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}  r_{j-\frac{3}{2}}.\label{g49}

By <a href="#Numerator1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Numerator1">[Numerator1]</a>, one has $$\label{g47}
            |P_{[p+1,x_2]}|\leq e^{L(\frac{1}{4}q_n+x) +C\varepsilon q_n}.$$ By <a href="#g47" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g47">[g47]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n} &|P_{[p+1,x_2]}|  (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j-1}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j-\frac{3}{2}})\nonumber\\
            %
            %
            \leq    &  e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+2Lx+C\varepsilon q_n}   r_{j-1}+ e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}  r_{j-\frac{3}{2}}.\label{g49}

\end{aligned}$$ By <a href="#g500" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g500">[g500]</a>, one has $$\label{g50}
            r_{j-\frac{3}{2}}\leq e^{C\varepsilon q_n+\frac{q_n}{2} L} r_{j-1}.$$ By <a href="#g49" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g49">[g49]</a>, <a href="#g50" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g50">[g50]</a> and the fact that $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{4}q_n$, one has $$\label{g51}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}|P_{[p+1,x_2]}|  (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j-1}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j-\frac{3}{2}})\leq e^{-(L-2\beta_{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} r_{j-1}.$$ We finish the estimate of <a href="#gg102" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg102">[gg102]</a>. Now we are in the position to bound <a href="#gg101" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg101">[gg101]</a>.

\end{aligned}$$ By <a href="#g500" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g500">[g500]</a>, one has $$\label{g50}
            r_{j-\frac{3}{2}}\leq e^{C\varepsilon q_n+\frac{q_n}{2} L} r_{j-1}.$$ By <a href="#g49" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g49">[g49]</a>, <a href="#g50" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g50">[g50]</a> and the fact that $0\leq x\leq \frac{1}{4}q_n$, one has $$\label{g51}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}|P_{[p+1,x_2]}|  (e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j-1}+ e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j-\frac{3}{2}})\leq e^{-(L-2\beta_{j} ) q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} r_{j-1}.$$ We finish the estimate of <a href="#gg102" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg102">[gg102]</a>. Now we are in the position to bound <a href="#gg101" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg101">[gg101]</a>.

By <a href="#g102" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g102">[g102]</a>, one has $$\label{g52}
            |P_{[x_1-(j-1)q_n,p-1-(j-1)q_n]}|\leq e^{L (\frac{3q_n}{4}+x)+C\varepsilon q_n}.$$ By Lemma <a href="#klem1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="klem1">7</a> and <a href="#g52" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g52">[g52]</a>, we have $$\label{g53}
            |P_{[x_1,p-1]}|\leq e^{L (\frac{3q_n}{4}+x)+C\varepsilon q_n}+e^{L(\frac{5q_n}{4}-x)-\beta_{j}q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}.$$ By <a href="#g53" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g53">[g53]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n} &e^{-L ( \frac{q_n}{4}+x) }|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|  r_{j}\nonumber\\
            \leq &  e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}(e^{L (\frac{3q_n}{4}+x)}+e^{L(\frac{5q_n}{4}-x)-\beta_{j}q_n }) e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}+x) } r_{j}\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{-(L-2\beta_{j})q_n+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j+e^{-(L-2\beta_{j})\frac{q_n}{2}-2L x+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j\nonumber\\
            \leq &  e^{-(L-2\beta_{j})\frac{q_n}{2}+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j.\label{g55}

\end{aligned}$$

This implies that the first term in <a href="#gg101" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg101">[gg101]</a> decays. We are going to bound the remaining term in <a href="#gg101" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg101">[gg101]</a>: $$e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}   e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) }|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|   r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}.$$

This implies that the first term in <a href="#gg101" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg101">[gg101]</a> decays. We are going to bound the remaining term in <a href="#gg101" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gg101">[gg101]</a>: $$e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}   e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) }|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|   r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}.$$

By Lemma <a href="#klem1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="klem1">7</a>, one has $$\label{2g38}
             |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}- P_{[{x}_1,p-1]}| \leq e^{L (\frac{5}{4}q_n-x)-\beta q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}.$$ By <a href="#2g38" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="2g38">[2g38]</a>, we have $$\begin{aligned}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}   &e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) }|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|   r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            \leq& e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}|P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|    e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber \\
            &+ e^{L (\frac{5}{4}q_n-x)-\beta q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}    e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j+\frac{1}{2}} \nonumber\\
            \leq & e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}  e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|    r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}  +e^{- (L-2\beta_{j}-C\varepsilon)\frac{q_n}{2}}r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}.\label{g61}

\end{aligned}$$ The second term in <a href="#g61" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g61">[g61]</a> decays, so we are going to bound the first term in <a href="#g61" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g61">[g61]</a>: $e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}  e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}|    r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}$.

Clearly, $x_1+q_n\in[jq_n-\frac{1}{4}q_n, jq_n]$. By Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a>, one has that $$\label{22g30}
            |\phi(x_1^\prime+q_n)|\leq r_{j} e^{-L  (\frac{q_n}{4}-x)+C\varepsilon q_n} +r_{j-\frac{1}{2}} e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4} +x)+C\varepsilon q_n} .$$

