By <a href="#g58" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g58">[g58]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n +2\beta_{j} q_n}e^{-L(\frac{q_n}{4}-x)}&   |P_{[x_1+q_n,p-1+q_n]}  |r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            \leq&e^{- \frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j}q_n+2L x+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j 
            +e^{-\frac{3}{2}L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            &+e^{-  L q_n+2\beta_{j}q_n +C\varepsilon q_n}r_{j+1}\nonumber\\
            \leq & e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j}q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}r_{j+1}+e^{- L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}r_{j},\label{g60}

\end{aligned}$$ where the last inequality holds by the fact that $r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}\leq e^{\frac{q_n}{2}L+C\varepsilon q_n} r_j$ and $0\leq x\leq \frac{q_n}{4}$.

By <a href="#g61" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g61">[g61]</a> and <a href="#g60" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g60">[g60]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
            e^{-\frac{3}{2} L q_n+2\beta_{j} q_n}&|P_{[x_1,p-1]}|   e^{-L (\frac{q_n}{4}-x) } r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            \leq &e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j}q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}(r_{j+1}+r_j)+e^{- (L-2\beta_{j}-C\varepsilon)\frac{q_n}{2}}r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}. \label{g62}

\end{aligned}$$

By <a href="#g63" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g63">[g63]</a>, <a href="#g51" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g51">[g51]</a>, <a href="#g55" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g55">[g55]</a> and <a href="#g62" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g62">[g62]</a> $$\begin{aligned}
            r_j \leq &e^{-(L  -2\beta_{j}-C\varepsilon)q_n}   (r_{j-1}+r_{j+1}) +  e^{-(L-2\beta_{j})\frac{q_n}{2}+C\varepsilon q_n} r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}\nonumber\\
            &+(e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j}q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}+e^{- \frac{1}{2}L q_n+\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}) r_{j}.\label{g128}

\end{aligned}$$ Since $$(e^{-L q_n+2\beta_{j}q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}+e^{- \frac{1}{2}L q_n+\beta_{j} q_n+C\varepsilon q_n}) r_{j}\leq \frac{1}{2}r_j,$$ by <a href="#g128" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="g128">[g128]</a>, one has $$\label{g70}
            r_j\leq 
            e^{-(L  -2\beta_{j}-C\varepsilon)q_n}   (r_{j-1}+r_{j+1}) +  e^{-(L-2\beta_{j}-C\varepsilon)\frac{q_n}{2}} r_{j+\frac{1}{2}}.$$

**Case 4**: $j_0\in[jq_n+\frac{1}{4}q_n, jq_n+\frac{1}{2}q_n]\cap I_2$

# Proof of Theorem <a href="#mainthm" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="mainthm">1</a>

Once we have Theorems <a href="#thm1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm1">8</a> and <a href="#thm2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm2">9</a> at hand, Theorem <a href="#mainthm" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="mainthm">1</a> follows from standard iterations. See   for example. For the convenience, we include a proof here.

<div class="proof">

***Proof of Theorem <a href="#mainthm" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="mainthm">1</a>**.* Without loss of generality, we only bound $\phi(k)$ with $k>0$. Let $n$ be such that $b_n\leq k<b_{n+1}$. Clearly, $\beta_j\leq \beta+\varepsilon$. By Theorems <a href="#thm1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm1">8</a> and <a href="#thm2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm2">9</a>, we have for any $j$ with $1\leq   j  \leq 2\frac{b_{n+1}}{q_n}+10$, $$\label{G.r_j2}
            r_{j-\frac{1}{2} }\leq  \exp\{ - \frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta-C\varepsilon) q_n \} \max\{r_{j-1},r_{j}\} ,$$ and $$\label{G.r_j1}
            r_{j }\leq  \max_{t\in O}\{\exp\{ -|t|(L-2\beta-C\varepsilon) q_n \} r_{j+t}\} ,$$ where $O=\{ \pm1,\pm\frac{1}{2}$}.

***Proof of Theorem <a href="#mainthm" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="mainthm">1</a>**.* Without loss of generality, we only bound $\phi(k)$ with $k>0$. Let $n$ be such that $b_n\leq k<b_{n+1}$. Clearly, $\beta_j\leq \beta+\varepsilon$. By Theorems <a href="#thm1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm1">8</a> and <a href="#thm2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm2">9</a>, we have for any $j$ with $1\leq   j  \leq 2\frac{b_{n+1}}{q_n}+10$, $$\label{G.r_j2}
            r_{j-\frac{1}{2} }\leq  \exp\{ - \frac{1}{2}(L-2\beta-C\varepsilon) q_n \} \max\{r_{j-1},r_{j}\} ,$$ and $$\label{G.r_j1}
            r_{j }\leq  \max_{t\in O}\{\exp\{ -|t|(L-2\beta-C\varepsilon) q_n \} r_{j+t}\} ,$$ where $O=\{ \pm1,\pm\frac{1}{2}$}.

Suppose $1 \leq \ell \leq \frac{b_{n+1}}{q_n}+4$. Let $j=\ell$ in (<a href="#G.r_j1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="G.r_j1">[G.r_j1]</a>) and (<a href="#G.r_j2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="G.r_j2">[G.r_j2]</a>), and iterate $2\ell$ times or until $j\leq 1$, we obtain $$\label{radd1}
            r_{\ell} \leq  (2\ell+2)q_n\exp\{- (L-2\beta -C\varepsilon) \ell q_n\},$$ and $$\label{radd2}
            r_{\ell-\frac{1}{2}}\leq  (2\ell+2)q_n\exp\{- (L-2\beta -C\varepsilon) (\ell -\frac{1}{2})q_n\}.$$ Notice that we have used the fact that $|r_{j}|\leq (j+1)q_n$ and $|r_{j-\frac{1}{2}}|\leq (j+1)q_n$.

**Case 1:** $k\geq \frac{q_n}{4}$ and ${\rm dist}(k, q_n\mathbb{Z}+\frac{q_n}{2}\mathbb{Z} )\leq     10\varepsilon q_n$.

In this case, applying <a href="#radd1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="radd1">[radd1]</a> and <a href="#radd2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="radd2">[radd2]</a>, one has $$\label{Decayoct1}
            | \phi(k)| ,  | \phi(k-1)|\leq   \exp\{- (L-2\beta -C\varepsilon)k\}.$$

**Case 2**: others

Applying Lemma <a href="#Le.resonant" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Le.resonant">4</a> with sufficiently small $\varepsilon$, and by <a href="#radd1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="radd1">[radd1]</a> and <a href="#radd2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="radd2">[radd2]</a>, one also has $$\label{Decayoct2}
            | \phi(k)|, | \phi(k-1)|\leq   \exp\{- (L-2\beta -C\varepsilon )k\}.$$ We finish the proof. ◻

