# Proof of Claims 1 and 2

Let $\frac{p_n}{q_n}$ be the continued fraction approximations to $\alpha$, then $$\label{GDC1}
        \forall 1\leq k <q_{n+1},  \text{dist}( k\alpha,\mathbb{Z})\geq  |q_n\alpha -p_n|,$$ and $$\label{GDC2}
        \frac{1}{2q_{n+1}}\leq|q_n\alpha-p_n| \leq\frac{1}{q_{n+1}}.$$

<div class="proof">

***Proof of Claim 1**.* By the construction of $I_1$ and $I_2$ in Claim 1, <a href="#GDC1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="GDC1">[GDC1]</a> and <a href="#GDC2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="GDC2">[GDC2]</a>, we have that

- for any $m \in I_1$, $$\label{Appenoct1}
                  \min_{\ell \in I_1\cup I_2}\ln |\sin \pi(2\theta +(\ell +  m)\alpha)|\geq -C\ln q_n,$$ and $$\label{Appenoct2}
                  \min_{\ell \neq m\atop \ell \in I_1\cup I_2} \ln |\sin
                  \pi (\ell-m)\alpha) | \geq -C\ln q_n;$$

- for any $m\in I_2$, $$\label{Appenoct3}
                  \min_{\ell \in I_1\cup I_2}\ln |\sin \pi(2\theta +(\ell +  m)\alpha)|_{\mathbb{R}/\mathbb{Z}}\geq  -\beta_{j} q_n-C\ln q_n,$$ and $$\label{Appenoct4}
                  \min_{\ell \neq m\atop \ell \in I_1\cup I_2} \ln |\sin
                  \pi (\ell-m )\alpha) | \geq -C\ln q_n.$$

We should mention that, for each $m\in I_2$, there is at most one $\ell\in I_1\cup I_2$ such that the lower bound of <a href="#Appenoct3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Appenoct3">[Appenoct3]</a> can be achieved.

***Proof of Claim 2**.* By the construction of $I_1$ and $I_2$ in Claim 2, <a href="#GDC1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="GDC1">[GDC1]</a> and <a href="#GDC2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="GDC2">[GDC2]</a>, we have that for $m \in I_1 \cup [jq_n-2s q_{n-n_0},jq_n-1]$, $$\label{Appenoct11}
            \min_{\ell \in I_1\cup I_2 }\ln |\sin \pi(2\theta +(\ell +  m)\alpha)|\geq \beta_{j} q_n-C\ln q_n,$$ and $$\label{Appenoct21}
            \min_{\ell \neq m\atop \ell \in I_1\cup I_2} \ln |\sin
            \pi (\ell-m)\alpha) | \geq  \beta_{j} q_n-C\ln q_n.$$ We should mention that, for each $m \in I_1 \cup [jq_n-2s q_{n-n_0},jq_n-1]$, there is at most one $\ell \in I_1\cup I_2$ such that the lower bound of <a href="#Appenoct11" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Appenoct11">[Appenoct11]</a> or <a href="#Appenoct21" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Appenoct21">[Appenoct21]</a> can be achieved.

We also have that for $m \in[jq_n, jq_n+2 sq_{n-n_0}-1]$, $$\label{Appenoct111}
        \min_{\ell \in I_1\cup I_2 }\ln |\sin \pi(2\theta +(\ell +  m)\alpha)|\geq \beta_{j} q_n-C\ln q_n,$$ and $$\label{Appenoct211}
        \min_{\ell \neq m\atop \ell \in I_1\cup I_2} \ln |\sin
        \pi (\ell-m)\alpha) | \geq   -C\ln q_n.$$ Moreover, for each $m \in[jq_n, jq_n+2 sq_{n-n_0}-1]$, there is at most two $\ell \in I_1\cup I_2$ such that the lower bound of <a href="#Appenoct111" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Appenoct111">[Appenoct111]</a>. Once we have <a href="#Appenoct11" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Appenoct11">[Appenoct11]</a>-<a href="#Appenoct211" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Appenoct211">[Appenoct211]</a> at hand, by the standard arguments (e.g. Appendices in  ), we have that for any $m\in I_1\cup I_2$, $${\rm Lag}_m\leq 2\beta_{j}q_n+ \varepsilon q_n.$$ ◻

